        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Email open rate</strong> is the percentage of recipients who open a specific email out of the total number of delivered emails. It is calculated as <strong>(unique opens ÷ delivered emails) × 100</strong> and tracked via a 1×1 transparent pixel embedded in the message. Industry benchmark sits at <strong>20-25%</strong>; anything above 25% indicates strong performance, while below 18% typically signals deliverability or list-hygiene problems.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Formula</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Unique opens / delivered</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Email Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Benchmark</div>
            <div class="tms-value">20-25%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Open rate is the first vote your subscribers cast. It measures whether your subject line, sender name, and preview text were worth two seconds of attention — long before the actual content of the email matters.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is email open rate?</h2>
        <p>Email open rate is the percentage of your delivered emails that recipients actually open. It is one of three foundational email metrics — alongside click-through rate and conversion rate — and the first indicator of whether a campaign is reaching people.</p>
        <p>The formula is straightforward:</p>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Open rate formula</span><br>
          Open Rate = ( <span class="uf-new">Unique Opens</span> / <span class="uf-status">Delivered Emails</span> ) × 100<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Example: 2,400 unique opens on 10,000 delivered</span><br>
          Open Rate = ( 2,400 / 10,000 ) × 100 = <span class="uf-status">24%</span>
        </div>
        <p>Opens are tracked via a 1×1 transparent pixel embedded in the email. When the recipient's email client loads images, the pixel loads too, registering an open.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Unique vs total opens</div>
          <p>Always track <strong>unique opens</strong> (each recipient counted once). Total opens include repeat opens by the same person, which inflates the number and makes campaign comparisons meaningless.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why email open rate matters</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Subject line diagnostic.</strong> Open rate is the direct feedback loop on subject-line effectiveness. Two subject lines on the same content will produce very different opens.</li>
          <li><strong>Sender-trust signal.</strong> Consistent high open rates tell mailbox providers your emails are wanted, which improves inbox placement for every future send.</li>
          <li><strong>List-health warning.</strong> A slow monthly decline in open rate is the earliest sign that engaged subscribers are drifting away and dead addresses are accumulating.</li>
          <li><strong>Deliverability early-warning.</strong> A sudden 10-point drop almost always means a spam-folder placement issue, not a content problem.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How open-rate tracking works</h2>
        <p>Every open registers when the recipient's email client loads a specific pixel embedded in your email:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Your ESP inserts a unique 1×1 transparent GIF into the email HTML, pointing to a tracking URL.</li>
          <li>When the recipient opens the email, their client requests the image from your ESP's server.</li>
          <li>Your ESP logs the request, timestamp, IP, and user-agent — attributing the open to that recipient.</li>
          <li>The dashboard aggregates unique opens across all recipients.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>This tracking model breaks when the recipient's client blocks images (some corporate mail clients) or pre-fetches them (Apple Mail Privacy Protection since 2021).</p>

